Here's the registration:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + data service instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // New ViewModel instance each time it's requested
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // New page instance each time it's navigated to
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`; shared state (caches, tokens) should live once. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation gets fresh state — no stale data leaking between visits. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pages hold UI state tied to their ViewModel; fresh page = fresh UI. |

**Rule of thumb:** stateless or per-request → `Transient`; expensive to create or shared state → `Singleton`. Avoid `Scoped` in MAUI — there's no built-in scope-per-page like in ASP.NET.

> **Tip:** For production, replace the raw `HttpClient` singleton with `builder.Services.AddHttpClient<IDataService, DataService>()` (from `Microsoft.Extensions.Http`) to get pooled handler management.
